						<svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor"><path d="M23.498 6.186a3.016 3.016 0 0 0-2.122-2.136C19.505 3.545 12 3.545 12 3.545s-7.505 0-9.377.505A3.017 3.017 0 0 0 .502 6.186C0 8.07 0 12 0 12s0 3.93.502 5.814a3.016 3.016 0 0 0 2.122 2.136c1.871.505 9.376.505 9.376.505s7.505 0 9.377-.505a3.015 3.015 0 0 0 2.122-2.136C24 15.93 24 12 24 12s0-3.93-.502-5.814zM9.545 15.568V8.432L15.818 12l-6.273 3.568z"/></svg>
						Watch on YouTube →
					</a>
				</div>

				<!-- Article Content -->
				<div style="font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;color:#4A3F3B;font-size:16px;line-height:1.95;">

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">Why This History Is Hidden</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						Japan's history curriculum has long struggled with the events of 1945 in Okinawa. For decades, textbook publishers and politicians have fought over what to include, what to minimize, and what to erase entirely.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 40px 0;">
						As someone born in Okinawa, I've watched this debate my entire life. What the textbooks say and what my grandparents' generation experienced are not the same story.
					</p>

					<!-- Fact 1 -->
					<div style="background:#1C2C4F;padding:32px;margin-bottom:32px;border-top:4px solid #8B1D25;">
						<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Cruel Fact 01</p>
						<h3 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 16px 0;">The Japanese Army Ordered Civilians to Commit Suicide</h3>
						<p style="color:#A8B8C8;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.9;margin:0 0 16px 0;"><em>"Shudan Jiketsu"</em> — mass suicide. The military distributed grenades to civilian families and taught them that capture by American soldiers meant torture, rape, and death. Propaganda so effective that families killed each other rather than surrender.</p>
						<p style="color:#A8B8C8;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.9;margin:0;">In 2007, the Japanese government attempted to remove references to the military's <em>direct involvement</em> in these deaths from high school textbooks. Okinawa erupted. 110,000 people protested in a single day — the largest demonstration in Okinawan history. The government eventually relented. But the pressure continues.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- Fact 2 -->
					<div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:32px;margin-bottom:32px;border-top:4px solid #8B1D25;">
						<p style="color:#8B1D25;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Cruel Fact 02</p>
						<h3 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Speaking Okinawan Language Got You Killed — By Japanese Soldiers</h3>
						<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.9;margin:0 0 16px 0;">As the battle collapsed into chaos, Japanese soldiers became paranoid. The Ryukyuan language — <em>Uchinaa-guchi</em> — sounded foreign to mainland Japanese ears. Soldiers began executing civilians they suspected of being spies based on nothing more than their language.</p>
						<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.9;margin:0;">This is why the suppression of Uchinaa-guchi, which began with Japanese annexation in 1879, carries such a traumatic weight in Okinawa. The very act of speaking your own language could mark you for death in your own homeland.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- Fact 3 -->
					<div style="background:#1C2C4F;padding:32px;margin-bottom:32px;border-top:4px solid #C8A86A;">
						<p style="color:#C8A86A;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Cruel Fact 03</p>
						<h3 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#F0EBE3;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Children Were Turned Into Soldiers and Nurses</h3>
						<p style="color:#A8B8C8;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.9;margin:0 0 16px 0;">The <strong>Himeyuri students</strong> — girls as young as 15 — were mobilized from their high schools and forced to serve as nurses in military field hospitals. They performed amputations without anesthesia, in dark caves, surrounded by the dying.</p>
						<p style="color:#A8B8C8;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.9;margin:0;">When the caves became untenable, the students were abruptly "discharged" by officers who left them to fend for themselves in the middle of active combat. Many died within hours. Their story is memorialized at the Himeyuri Peace Museum in Itoman — a monument to what happens when a state treats its children as expendable.</p>
					</div>

					<!-- Fact 4 -->
					<div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid #D0C5BA;padding:32px;margin-bottom:48px;border-top:4px solid #8B1D25;">
						<p style="color:#8B1D25;font-family:'Noto Sans JP',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Cruel Fact 04</p>
						<h3 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Okinawa Was Never Meant to Be Saved — Only Sacrificed</h3>
						<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.9;margin:0 0 16px 0;">The most hidden fact of all: the Japanese military's strategy was never to defend Okinawa. It was to sacrifice it. The plan, called <em>"Fukkaku"</em> (Endurance War), was explicitly designed to delay the American advance — at the cost of Okinawan lives — to buy time for mainland Japan to prepare.</p>
						<p style="color:#4A3F3B;font-family:'Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.9;margin:0;">This wasn't a secret after the war. The documentation exists. Yet the narrative that Japan fought to "protect" Okinawa persists in certain political circles. For Okinawans who know their history, this rewriting is not just inaccurate. It is a second betrayal.</p>
					</div>

					<h2 style="font-family:'Shippori Mincho','Noto Serif JP',serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:700;color:#1C2C4F;margin:0 0 20px 0;padding-top:8px;border-top:2px solid #D0C5BA;">Why It Matters Now</h2>
					<p style="margin:0 0 24px 0;">
						These are not ancient grievances. Japan continues to debate how to teach this history. Okinawa continues to carry a disproportionate military burden. The conversation about what happened in 1945 is inseparable from the conversation about what Okinawa deserves today.
					</p>
					<p style="margin:0 0 48px 0;">
						Unmuting Ryukyu exists because these stories deserve to be told — not as political tools, but as human truth. If you read this far, you now know something that many Japanese citizens do not.
					</p>

